INSERT INTO `accrediting_agency_hqaa` (`id`, `util_reg_agencies_id`, `short_code`, `standard_number`, `standard_description`, `description`, `effective_date`, `is_active`, `deactivation_date`)
VALUES
	(1,586,'org_1','ORG 1','Mission and Vision','The organization has a mission/vision statement that describes the organization\'s current focus and future goals. The organization reviews this statement annually.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(2,586,'org_2','ORG 2','Compliance with Permits, Licenses and Supplier/Provider Agreements','The organization demonstrates that it is in compliance with all required federal, state and local licenses, permits, certifications and registration requirements, and demonstrates that those documents are active. All licenses, permits, and registrations shall be available and posted as required by law. This would include compliance with Medicare Enrollment Standards for those providers who have a valid Medicare provider number and/or an NPI number. The supplier shall provide copies, upon request, to government officials or their authorized agents (i.e. HQAA).','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(3,586,'org_3','ORG 3','Leadership and Administrative Structure','The organization provides leadership and designates one or more persons with authority, responsibility, and accountability to direct the organization and its key activities and operations. The organization must list an administrative structure that includes a current organizational chart recording all job titles of positions or classifications in the organization. The chart provides information about administrative management and chain of command.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(4,586,'org_4','ORG 4','Leadership/Governance','Leadership/governance ensures that the organization is governed and managed in a manner that promotes continuity and responsibility and is accountable for the organization\'s operations.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(5,586,'org_5','ORG 5','Compliance Program Guide','The organization will maintain a written compliance program which complies with all seven elements of this standard.<ol><li>The development and distribution of written standards of conduct, as well as written policies and procedures that promote the organization\'s commitment to compliance and to training that addresses specific areas of potential fraud, such as the claims submission process, code \"gaming\", and financial relationships with its providers</li><li>The designation of a compliance officer and other appropriate bodies, e.g., a compliance committee (dependent upon the size of the organization). The compliance officer will have responsibility of operating and monitoring the compliance program. The compliance officer will have a direct line of reporting to the CEO/owner/Board of Directors (in the case of a publicly held company, the compliance officer may report to the Board of Director\'s audit committee)</li><li>The development, implementation, and documentation of regular, effective compliance education and training programs for all affected staff</li><li>The creation and maintenance of a process, such as a hotline, to receive complaints and the adoption of procedures to provide limited anonymity of complainants and to protect callers from retaliation</li><li>The development of a system to respond to allegations of improper/illegal activities and the enforcement of appropriate disciplinary action against employees who have violated internal compliance policies, applicable statutes, regulations or federal, state or private payer health care program requirements</li><li>The use of audits and/or other risk evaluation techniques and the existence of a quality program that will help in monitoring the organization\'s compliance program and assist in the reduction of identified problem areas</li><li>A policy/procedure that supports investigations and the corrections of identified systemic problems such as submission of false claims</li></ol>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(6,586,'org_6','ORG 6','Conflicts of Interest','The company must identify and define in a policy any potential for professional conflicts of interest by its employees or customers and ensure that they are reviewed and addressed as required by law and regulation and in a timely manner.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(7,586,'org_7','ORG 7','Ethics','The organization maintains an ethics policy and establishes procedures that define ethics and the organization\'s response to ethical issues. This policy is a part of employee orientation and education.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(8,586,'pro_1','PRO 1','Policies and Procedures','The organization will provide a policy and procedure manual (paper, electronic, or other format as deemed appropriate by the organization) as written documentation of all professional programs, administrative processes and requirements, and scope of services. This manual will include policies and procedures and the implementation dates and revision dates for all policies. The organization will review these policies and procedures annually.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(9,586,'pro_2','PRO 2','Contracted Business Agreements','The organization has a legal contract in place that states the responsibilities of all parties doing business with the organization or on behalf of the organization, either internally or externally, when related to patient care and equipment. Business agreements for the organization are approved by authorized individuals. The organization\'s business agreements include the following:<ul><li>Terms of agreement/length of contract</li><li>Requirements of all parties</li><li>Services/equipment provided</li><li>Responsibilities for preventive maintenance on equipment (when applicable)</li><li>Payment/rates</li><li>Signature of all parties</li><li>Date of execution</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(10,586,'pro_3','PRO 3','Medical Records','The organization will maintain accurate and secure medical records, through policy and process. All medical records within the organization will be kept in a uniform manner. The medical records policy will address:<ul><li>Security, including process regarding theft or destruction</li><li>Staff access to files</li><li>Privacy & confidentiality</li><li>Protected Health Information disclosure processes</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(11,586,'pro_4','PRO 4','Retention of Client Records','The organization will retain all records of all clients served, within confidentiality and privacy practices for at least seven (7) years or longer as required by law or applicable regulation. These records include those for services and billing. All records must be maintained in an easily retrievable manner. Pediatric patient records must be kept on file until the patient is at least seven (7) years past the age of majority or as required by state law.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(12,586,'pro_5','PRO 5','Disclosure to Outside Entities','The organization has a policy and process that allows for full disclosure of any or all of the organization\'s documents to all applicable accreditation organizations, government agencies and/or payer representatives, as allowable by state and federal regulations. This policy addresses any requirements pertaining to the disclosure of any documents pertinent to any review, investigation or appropriate request for required documentation as needed. The supplier shall comply with payer (i.e. Medicare) disclosure of ownership and control information requirements found at 42 CFR 420.201 through 420.206.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(13,586,'fs_1','FS 1','Financial Management','The organization has a policy and process that describes its financial management plan to ensure viability and manages revenues and expenses on an ongoing basis, as they relate to patient/client services. This policy describes:<ul><li>Practices to ensure accurate billing and accounting with reconciliation of charges for equipment services and supplies with invoices, receipts, and deposits</li><li>Maintenance of financial records that are accurate, complete, and current</li><li>A cash or accrual based accounting system</li><li>A process that links equipment and items to recipients</li><li>Designating one or more individuals in leadership positions to address compliance issues</li></ul><p>The organization has an annual operational budget that is appropriate to the needs of the clients and is determined by business size and scope of service.</p>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(14,586,'fs_2','FS 2','Financial Management Review','The organization has a policy indicating that all financial management documentation is reviewed and recorded by leadership. The policy should identify that the review includes:<ul><li>Accurate billing and accounting practices with reconciliations of charges</li><li>Information gained from a cash or accrual based accounting system</li><li>Operating budget</li><li>Mechanism to track revenues and expenses</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(15,586,'hr_1','HR 1','Policies, Procedures and Support Tools','The organization\'s leadership has appointed an individual(s) who is responsible for oversight of human resource materials, policies, and programs. These policies and programs include:<ul><li>Implementation of policies that specify personnel qualifications, training, experience, and continuing education requirements consistent with the specialized equipment, items, and services it provides to clients</li><li>Policies that describe job descriptions, competencies, disciplinary action measures, and employee orientation</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(16,586,'hr_2','HR 2','Competency Program','The organization describes in policy their program to ensure that only competent personnel provide direct patient/client services for the organization. Competency must be evaluated through direct observation. Technical personnel shall be competent to deliver and set-up, train, maintain, and troubleshoot equipment/items for patients/clients and/or caregivers. Professional personnel shall be licensed, certified, or registered and function within their scope of practice as required by the state standard under which the professional is licensed or certified. The supplier shall maintain current copies and other verification of licenses, registrations, certifications, and competency assessments. An organization\'s competency program:<ul><li>Is written</li><li>Assesses the competency of each designated service provider upon hire and annually</li><li>Is evaluated and reviewed/revised/updated at least biennially (every 2 years) or sooner as needed</li><li>Includes the services and tasks performed by each designated staff member based on job function or category</li><li>Tools used are signed and dated by both the staff member and the evaluator</li><li>When outside evaluators are used, a copy of their credentials is on file with the organization</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(17,586,'hr_3','HR 3','Contracted Staff','The organization has a policy describing written requirements for contractors who function as organization staff or provide services on behalf of the organization. This includes providing proper orientation on the organization\'s appropriate policies and procedures, a competency assessment to ensure that the contracted staff\'s personal qualifications and skills match their job duties and responsibilities, and any other requirements as defined by leadership.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(18,586,'hr_4','HR 4','Background Checks','The organization has a policy describing how it conducts criminal background checks if mandated by state law for all candidates for employment in all states where the organization has administrative offices or provides services. These checks ensure that no candidate is hired who could put the client or organization at risk.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(19,586,'hr_5','HR 5','Annual Educational Programs','The organization will inform all employees of all annual educational requirements and provide that education at no charge to their staff. The organization\'s annual program will offer no less than six (6) hours of education for all staff members, regardless of their position. Educational topics provided must be relevant to the employee\'s job function. Records of staff attendance at all educational programs are kept. The organization makes every effort to provide programs at times that do not pose an undue burden on staff for attendance. The annual educational calendar will include programs in:<ul><li>Infection control and blood borne pathogens</li><li>OSHA and safety issues to include fire safety, disaster preparedness, and office security</li><li>HIPAA, privacy and security</li><li>Any new products or services the organization plans to provide</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(20,586,'hr_6','HR 6','Job Descriptions','The organization provides written job descriptions for every position in the organization. Each job description contains:<ul><li>Job title</li><li>Reporting requirements</li><li>Expectations of work hours</li><li>Basic requirements for the position</li><li>Requirements for licenses or certifications that must be maintained in order to perform duties</li><li>A complete list of the major tasks or duties that are expected to be performed</li><li>A place for signature and date for employee to sign during orientation to the position</li><li>Any relevant information that may provide details to comply with the Americans with Disabilities Act (such as exposure to physical demands and activities)</li><li>Expectations for any education requirements, which includes continuing education requirements specific to duties</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(21,586,'hr_7','HR 7','Performance Reviews','The organization conducts annual or biennial (every 2 years) performance reviews for each staff member. These reviews will be documented and include the staff member and supervisor\'s signature and date.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(22,586,'hr_8','HR 8','Personnel Files','The organization will maintain an individual personnel file for each active, inactive, or terminated staff member. Files for all current staff are maintained on site in a secure environment that provides confidentiality, limited access, and safeguards against loss or damage. Inactive or terminated employee files may be stored on or off site while similar safeguards are demonstrated. Off-site files must be able to be returned to the site within 2 business days. Terminated files are kept on file seven years or more if required by law or regulations. Each personnel file will contain:<ul><li>Application</li><li>Resume of prior employment and training if this information is not provided on an application. This must document that the employee qualifies for the position based on the appropriate training, proper licensing, and required degree or experience when applicable</li><li>Evidence of interview by organization staff member</li><li>Two or more documented reference checks</li><li>Copy of returned criminal background check (when applicable) and validation is performed</li><li>Copy of current professional license or certification required including the signature and date of the individual performing the validation, and proof of verification that the license is current</li><li>Signed and dated orientation checklist that lists all items reviewed</li><li>Signed and dated job description</li><li>Signed and dated annual performance review(s) (as applicable)</li><li>Any required forms the organization deems necessary such as conflict of interest, confidentiality, computer or equipment usage, etc.</li></ul><p>The file may also contain copies of training, competency, education classes attended, awards received, letters received regarding performance from outside individuals or clients or other items as appropriate.</p><p>Additional item that would be collected but maintained in a separate, secure file (which may be the health information file):</p><ul><li>INS citizenship verification (I-9), since a date of birth is required on the form and supportive documentation</li></ul><p>Additionally, a file is maintained that contains any items containing health information. These can include:</p><ul><li>Pre-employment health screening</li><li>Any ongoing health communications, such as worker\'s compensation issues</li><li>A copy of a state-issued driver\'s license (when required)</li><li>Results of any drug testing</li><li>Proof of vaccination for Hepatitis B or declination form as appropriate</li><li>Documentation of TB testing/screening, as required by organization policy</li><li>Criminal background check results (if date of birth is listed)</li><li>Payroll enrollment forms that list date of birth</li><li>Insurance enrollment information (if date of birth is listed)</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(23,586,'ics_1','ICS 1','Safety/Infection Control Officer','The organization has a policy describing responsibilities of the safety/infection control officer. The policy delineates responsibilities for the monitoring and surveillance of all safety and infection control issues and gives a complete listing of duties and responsible parties. In a small organization, this may be the owner or designee. In a larger organization, these duties can be delegated to be the responsibility of more than one person.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(24,586,'ics_2','ICS 2','Maintaining a Clean, Safe and Organized Work Environment','The organization will promote safety and minimize risks and hazards while complying with all regulations concerning a safe, clean and organized work environment. The organization will ensure that:<ul><li>There are posted exit strategies throughout the physical location, with clearly marked routes and exits. Fire extinguishers, smoke detectors and sprinklers are tested annually (as applicable)</li><li>First aid supplies are provided</li><li>An eye wash station is available in areas where cleaning and disinfecting occur and when required by law and regulation</li><li>Hazardous waste is handled and disposed of properly</li><li>The environment should be clean of clutter. Regular trash removal should be consistent and thorough</li><li>Any food items kept on company property must be stored appropriately and away from\rcontaminated areas and all patient or client products</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(25,586,'ics_3','ICS 3','Receiving Clean or Contaminated Items','The organization has a policy that describes a process for separating clean items from dirty or contaminated items and the proper infection control practices. The policy describes the following:<ul><li>Receiving and cleaning/disinfecting dirty or contaminated equipment and devices in accordance with the manufacturer guidelines or requirements</li><li>How all items in the facility are kept in clearly marked locations that prevent the contamination of clean items by dirty/contaminated items</li><li>Necessary cleaning methods of equipment are appropriate, safe and efficient</li><li>Personal protective equipment that is readily available and used appropriately by staff members to clean and decontaminate returned equipment or devices</li><li>Documentation, whether on a tag, in a log book, a computer, or other means that shows the date and initials of the staff member who has performed the evaluation that the item is\rclean and ready for patient use</li><li>Material safety data sheets (MSDS) on site for all chemicals or products used in cleaning or repair in the office, retail area, warehouse and vehicles</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(26,586,'ics_4','ICS 4','OSHA, Safety and Infectious Disease','The organization maintains appropriate policies concerning all relevant safety and OSHA issues. These would include policies such as TB screening and/or treatment, any infectious diseases or issues as required by state law, required health screening, Hepatitis B vaccinations and drug testing (as required by insurance carriers or other).','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(27,586,'ics_5','ICS 5','Product/Item Recall','The organization has a process for handling all device and oxygen recalls or discontinuations for safety purposes by the manufacturer or the Food and Drug Administration in accordance with the instructions of the recall or discontinuation notice. The following is included:<ul><li>In the event that a replacement item is available and appropriate, the organization makes a reasonable attempt to replace the item</li><li>Oxygen is tracked by lot number in accordance with FDA requirements</li><li>The organization tracks equipment by lot or serial number as governed by the Medical\rDevice Act and implements all recalls or discontinuations in accordance with the FDA or manufacturer</li><li>All applicable notices or memos regarding discontinued or recalled items will be kept on file by the organization. The organization will document the actions taken for recalls being retrieved or separated from inventory and destroyed or returned to the manufacturer etc., as per the recall instructions</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(28,586,'ics_6','ICS 6','Injury/Exposure/Incident Program','The organization has a policy in place that describes the program to manage any injury or exposure to hazardous material or an unexpected event that may occur with staff on or off site. The policy will include:<ul><li>The organization\'s definition of an unexpected event, injuries and hazardous exposure issues</li><li>How the risks are identified by the safety officer and reviewed with staff members who may be at risk for exposure or injury due to their job duties</li><li>The procedure for response and reporting to all proper authorities as required by law and regulation of an unexpected event, injury or exposure</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(29,586,'ics_7','ICS 7','Disaster Plan','The organization has a written program that is tested annually to ensure the safety of staff and clients in the event of a disaster or emergency. The organization will define in writing what qualifies as a disaster or emergency. The organization\'s disaster plan would be implemented when needed and will:<ul><li>Identify high risk patients who may be affected by the disaster</li><li>Identify services that may be delayed or interrupted as a result of the disaster</li><li>Identify staff who may be affected as a result of the disaster, and how their duties would be covered if they could not come to work, e.g., the only two (2) registered therapists are at the local hospital and not allowed to leave due to the hospital\'s disaster plan</li><li>Identify who activates/deactivates the disaster plan and the role of the staff</li><li>Have arrangements with alternative suppliers in the event that the supplier cannot service its own customers as the result of an emergency or disaster</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(30,586,'ics_8','ICS 8','Emergency Preparedness','The organization has an emergency preparedness plan in place for securing or evacuating all business locations in the event of an emergency or disaster. This plan describes potential specific situations in which the preparedness plan would be implemented. It is specific for each business location, tested and evaluated annually, and updated as needed. All staff is aware of this plan including their roles and responsibilities. The organization has an identified safety officer (or combination of persons) who is responsible for managing the organization\'s safety plan which addresses the following items:<ul><li>General preparedness at the organization and in the patient\'s home</li><li>Equipment/device replacement preparedness</li><li>Staff preparedness</li><li>Emergency response procedures</li><li>Fire or emergency evacuation plan per site</li><li>Identification of alternate sites as needed</li><li>Hazardous materials</li><li>Equipment failure at the organization and in the patient\'s home</li><li>Safety planning for staff at the organization and while in the field</li><li>Security of patient data, information systems, facility, vehicles, and equipment in the possession of a staff member while transporting to a client</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(31,586,'qm_1','QM 1','Quality/Performance Improvement Program','The company will implement a quality improvement program designed to specifically monitor and record the quality of its services and programs and measures the outcomes of consumer services, billing practices, and adverse events. This program will report collected data of the following performance measurements (at a minimum):<ol><li>The satisfaction/complaints of patients/clients regarding products and services and the satisfaction/complaints of referral sources or staff satisfaction</li><li>Achieving financial performance targets<ul><li>Frequency of billing and coding errors</li><li>Percentage of collections</li><ul><li>Business activities or other similar functions or services such as staff performance, service issues, or information exchanges that focus on client/customer access to equipment, items, services, and information</li><li>Timeliness of response to customers regarding problems/issues/concerns</li><li>Adverse events to beneficiaries due to inadequate or malfunctioning equipment, items, or services (e.g., injuries, accidents, signs and symptoms of infection, hospitalizations). This may be identified through follow-up with the prescribing physician, other healthcare team members, or the beneficiary or caregiver</li></ol>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(32,586,'qm_2','QM 2','Adverse Events','The organization defines, monitors, and provides the appropriate follow-up for all sentinel/adverse events pertaining to its product line(s) or delivery of service. All sentinel/adverse events are reported to the proper regulating body(ies), the organization\'s leadership, and accrediting body. The organization\'s performance improvement program meets all relative payer requirements regarding monitoring, reporting and follow-up.<p>The investigation should be initiated within 24 hours after a supplier becomes aware of an injury or incident, or infection resulting in a client\'s hospitalization or death. For other occurrences, the supplier shall investigate within 72 hours after being made aware of the incident, infection or injury. The investigation includes all necessary information, pertinent conclusions about what happened, and whether changes in systems or processes are needed. The supplier should consider possible links between the items and services furnished and the adverse event.</p>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(33,586,'qm_3','QM 3','Leadership Quality Program Review','The organization\'s leadership conducts a review and analysis annually of the data collected quarterly in the quality improvement program. (See QM 1) There are documented operational adjustments or recorded summarizations from the results.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(34,586,'bc_1','BC 1','Accurate and Complete Billing Records','The organization maintains accurate and complete billing records that are stored in a safe and secure manner and are audited for accuracy on a scheduled basis. The client billing record will contain, but is not limited to:<ul><li>Client name, address, date of birth</li><li>Pertinent diagnosis</li><li>Equipment/device/service provided/delivered</li><li>Payer information and client information for invoice processing</li><li>Copies of all invoices sent to client and all payer sources</li><li>Copies of receipts of all payments made by client, payers or any others with dates of\rpayment(s) received. Client billing records may be kept separate from the client medical records</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(35,586,'bc_2','BC 2','Client Charges and Collection of Payments','The organization has policies and procedures in place to inform clients of eligibility for services, all charges, any out-of-pocket expenses they may incur and the manner in which those payments are collected and implements this process with each client. This process includes policies and procedures regarding the collection of payments from clients including those for cash, co-payments, cross-overs and any secondary or tertiary payments, and the process for managing hardships. The process also describes the requirement for obtaining advanced beneficiary notices (ABN\'s).','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(36,586,'bc_3','BC 3','Compliance with All Payer Requirements and Regulations','The organization is compliant with all current payer requirements and ensures that staff are properly trained and informed.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(37,586,'ps_1','PS 1','Client Acceptance/Services','The organization admits for service only clients who require the services within the scope of practice that the organization, or its contracted providers, can provide. The organization describes in policy the standardized processes that include, but are not limited to:<ul><li>Timely intake and acceptance of referrals or requests for service</li><li>Informing clients of acceptance or denial</li><li>Validating client eligibility for services</li><li>Verification of client benefits to be used for payment</li><li>Verification of the receipt of the items or services by client</li><li>Provides for appropriate and informed termination of equipment or services to a client</li><li>Maintaining client dignity, privacy, and respect</li><li>Ensures that all staff respect client property while providing services in client residence</li><li>The organization provides a loan or replacement of any equipment or device in the event of failure, breakage, or questionable performance for any item or loan to a client</li><li>Informing in a timely manner referral source (and physician if required) if item/service cannot be provided as ordered, but in no case more than five (5) calendar days, if it cannot provide the equipment, items or services that are prescribed for a client</li><li>Timely follow-up as needed consistent with the types of equipment, items and service(s) provided, and recommendations from the prescribing physician or healthcare team members</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(38,586,'ps_2','PS 2','Physician Orders and Coordination of Care','The organization accepts orders from physicians for products and services within its identified scope of services. The organization documents all orders appropriately and maintains complete orders for services, equipment, devices, medications and drugs (such as oxygen). All verbal orders are validated via physician signature. The organization has processes to ensure that all physician orders are:<ul><li>Obtained</li><li>Validated or clarified, if needed</li><li>Updated when applicable</li><li>Filed</li><li>Maintained</li><li>Managed through a controlled process for obtaining a signature that complies with all appropriate regulation</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(39,586,'ps_3','PS 3','Plan of Care','The organization ensures that all services provided are:<ul><li>Under a physician\'s order</li><li>Individualized to the patient receiving the care</li><li>Consistent with other identified beneficiary needs, risks, and limitations of which\rthe supplier is aware</li><li>Reviewed periodically for revisions, updates, changes and modification and the criteria for changes are defined</li><li>Updates or revisions are collaborative with the physician, as needed</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(40,586,'ps_4','PS 4','Client/Caregiver Education, Training and Safety','The organization provides appropriate education, training and safety instruction to clients or their caregivers as required by their payers on all equipment, devices, products, or services provided. This process clearly identifies the client or caregiver training expectations. On admission to service the organization educates each client and caregiver, when applicable, regarding:<ul><li>Client\'s rights and responsibilities</li><li>Normal business hours and contact information for the organization</li><li>Payer required documents (i.e. NSC supplier standards)</li><li>Client\'s role in participation in plan of service</li><li>Options for rental and purchase of all equipment/devices provided</li><li>Proper set up and use of the equipment or device that complies with the physician\'s order</li><li>Infection control issues, potential safety risks, and potential hazards for beneficiaries</li><li>Residence safety and other appropriate safety considerations</li><li>Handling emergencies and emergency preparedness</li><li>Equipment or device maintenance/cleaning/troubleshooting/potential hazards</li><li>Process for reporting injuries while using the equipment or device</li><li>Complaint process</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(41,586,'ps_5','PS 5','After Hours','The organization provides the client with information regarding after-hours access and emergency coverage. For organizations providing oxygen and life sustaining equipment, the organization will be available to the customer 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, ensuring that calls are returned within 60 minutes (or less if required by state law). The organization maintains a log which includes the time the call was received, the time the call was returned, the concern or reason for the call, and the resolution. The on-call program provides that a visit will be made when problems that arise after hours cannot wait until the next service day and is duly documented.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(42,586,'ps_6','PS 6','Client Medical Records','The organization maintains a complete and accurate medical record for each client. The content of the patient\'s record will include: (when applicable)<ul><li>Client name, date of birth</li><li>Place of residence where equipment/device/service is being delivered/provided</li><li>Client diagnosis and pertinent medical history</li><li>Client assessment and/or evaluation on admission to services (when applicable)</li><li>Client allergies to medications (when applicable)</li><li>Date equipment/device/service was ordered/received</li><li>Equipment/device/service delivered or provided and signed receipt of delivery</li><li>Date of delivery with verification of receipt</li><li>Prescribing physician and signed order</li><li>Certificate of Medical Necessity or other required billing documents</li><li>Equipment/device/service serial/lot number</li><li>Documentation of verification that the equipment/device was functional at the time of\rthe delivery</li><li>Documentation that the client/caregiver was educated on proper equipment/device use, safety and client\'s responsibility for use and maintenance</li><li>Documentation of client/caregiver\'s understanding of teaching or need for additional teaching</li><li>Verification of receipt by the patient or caregiver of all paperwork, educational materials, payment information, warranties, safety assessments, instructions, privacy policy, etc that the organization provides to the patient at the start of services</li><li>General communication with the patient and family, including follow-up, complaints, etc.</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(43,586,'ps_7','PS 7','Electronic Medical Records','The organization provides the following safeguards for electronic records:<ul><li>Clear attestation statement and process utilizing a unique and individual identification</li><li>A time and date stamp that reflects the time and dates each entry is made to the record and by whom</li><li>Adequate safeguards that the system cannot be breached or compromised</li><li>Adequate safeguards that provide for back up of all electronic data and a process for recovery in the event that the system fails and data must be re-loaded or re-entered</li><li>Procedures for interruptions in electrical power that may impede access to electronic data and a process to identify the most critical information and systems needed to continue to provide patient care and treatment</li><li>Appropriate systems and processes in place to ensure the confidentiality and security of business programs and client information</li><li>Adequate safeguards to ensure that the system, its processors and other related devices are secure and adequate for the need and size of the organization</li><li>HIPAA compliant</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(44,586,'ps_8','PS 8','Grievances and Complaints','The organization receives grievances and/or complaints from clients and customers in a standardized process. The organization maintains documentation of such issues which includes:<ul><li>Date complaint received, by whom</li><li>Name, address, and contact number of individual contacting organization</li><li>Issue or complaint or grievance</li><li>Investigation and response to complaint</li><li>Resolution of issue with attached documentation when necessary</li><li>Any payer requirements (i.e. Medicare HIC number)</li></ul><p>Within five (5) calendar days of receiving a beneficiary\'s complaint, the supplier shall notify the beneficiary, using either oral, telephone, e-mail, fax, or letter format, that it has received the complaint that it is investigating. Within 14 calendar days, the supplier shall provide written notification to the beneficiary of the results of its investigation and response. The supplier shall maintain documentation of all complaints that it receives, copies of the investigations, and responses to beneficiaries.</p>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(45,586,'ps_9','PS 9','Coordination of Care','The organization documents the coordination of care between all those involved in the delivery of services or equipment/devices to the client. The organization documents communication with the client and between providers in a standardized manner within the client medical record.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(46,586,'ps_10','PS 10','Marketing and Advertising Materials','The organization ensures that the information listed in its advertising and marketing materials correctly reflects the products and services currently offered by the organization in an honest and ethical manner. The organization ensures that only those items and services that are within its scope of services are marketed or advertised to the public.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(47,586,'mm_1','MM 1','Warehouse/Storage','The organization ensures that all warehouse and storage areas:<ul><li>Are organized and secure</li><li>Segregate clean items from dirty or contaminated items</li><li>Are temperature controlled and regulated as required</li><li>Show clearly designated exit routes in the event of fire, electrical failure or other emergency</li><li>Maintain all appropriate safety equipment as needed (smoke detectors, fire extinguishers, eye wash stations, etc.)</li><li>Have MSDS (Material Safety Data Sheets) available</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(48,586,'mm_2','MM 2','Selection of Equipment, Device, and Supplies','The organization selects equipment, devices, and supplies for clients as ordered by the physician. All equipment, devices, and supplies are based on client need and accommodate any contractual payer requirements. The organization obtains copies of features, warranties, and instructions for all items from the manufacturers. All equipment, devices, and services provided for client use are stored in clearly identified patient ready areas. All equipment, supplies and devices are labeled with the organization\'s name, address and phone number as appropriate. All items meet applicable Food and Drug Administration (FDA) regulations and medical device effectiveness and safety standards.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(49,586,'mm_3','MM 3','Equipment/Device Inventory Tracking and Monitoring Functions','The supplier shall implement an equipment and item management program that promotes the safe use of equipment and items and minimizes safety risks and hazards both for its staff and for clients. The organization is able to locate all equipment/devices in the organization\'s current inventory, whether owned or leased by the organization. The organization monitors all equipment and devices in the inventory for proper functioning. This includes all rental equipment/devices that are in use at a client\'s residence, those items in inventory that are considered patient ready, and those items that are in the process of cleaning, disinfecting, repair, or routine maintenance. The inventory tracking process includes the equipment, device or item name; manufacturer; lot, serial or batch number; expiration date; and present location or status of each item as applicable.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(50,586,'mm_4','MM 4','Preventive Maintenance, Repair and Testing','The organization provides scheduled preventive maintenance, repairs and testing of all equipment and devices provided to clients as recommended by the equipment or device manufacturer. The organization has a process to identify equipment scheduled for maintenance, and provides the needed maintenance or repair of the equipment and devices according to the manufacturer\'s guidelines or recommendations, whether the item is owned or leased by the organization. The organization provides the client with a replacement item when equipment/device in use is scheduled for maintenance or repair. The organization has a process to repair equipment and devices that are reported as damaged or malfunctioning. The organization maintains a file of all current manufacturer\'s maintenance, warranties, repair, and testing instructions and recommendations for all equipment, devices, and supplies they provide.<p>Only qualified staff members perform repairs or maintenance on equipment and devices according to the manufacturer\'s guidelines. The maintenance and repair data for each piece of equipment or device, as appropriate, includes:</p><ul><li>Equipment name, manufacturer, and serial number</li><li>Date equipment went into service</li><li>Projected dates of manufacturer recommended scheduled maintenance cleaning and calibration</li><li>Dates maintenance performed<ul><li>Dates and reason of performed repairs</li><li>Disposition after maintenance or repair</li></ul></ul><p>Report and return to manufacturer of any defective item and disposition, as appropriate.</p>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(51,586,'mm_5','MM 5','Back-up Systems Available, Replaced and Assigned','The organization provides a loan or replacement of any equipment or device in the event of failure, breakage or questionable performance for any item on rental or loan to a client. The organization accepts returns of equipment and replacement of items as required by the payer.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(52,586,'mo_1','MO 1','Mail Order','If the organization provides delivery of products via US Mail, courier or national commercial delivery services, the organization ensures the following:<ul><li>Recipient is aware and agrees to all shipping, handling or other charges</li><li>Recipient receives appropriate educational materials within the shipment for use of the product(s) and any relevant contact numbers or additional education or assistance</li><li>Tracking mechanisms are in place to ensure that the product(s) are delivered to the recipient in a timely manner</li><li>The organization provides a clear process for return or replacement of item(s) sent and recipient is aware of all policies and procedures for return or replacement of the product(s) received</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(53,586,'del_1','DEL 1','Delivery Documentation','The organization requires documentation to be maintained of all scheduled deliveries, including the client\'s name, address, item to be delivered and any additional needed information in any type of format the organization desires. The organization ensures that this information remains secure at all times and is not communicated to individuals other than appropriate staff members involved in the care of the client. This documentation is kept on file for minimum of seven (7) years or longer if required by state, federal or payer requirements.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(54,586,'del_2','DEL 2','Transportation, Handling and Delivery of Equipment/Devices','The organization ensures that all equipment and devices are handled according to manufacturer guidelines as well as federal, state and local laws and regulations. All equipment and devices are labeled properly; handled, transported, and delivered safely; and secured in vehicles appropriately. All hazardous materials are labeled according to industry guidelines and law and regulation. Infection control precautions are observed in reference to clean and dirty boundaries within vehicles while transporting, loading, unloading, handling and delivering equipment/devices.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(55,586,'del_3','DEL 3','Client Residence Assessment','The organization requires that all delivery personnel are able to provide an adequate assessment of the client residence to ensure that any safety issues are identified and addressed as per payer requirements.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(56,586,'del_4','DEL 4','Equipment/Device Delivery and Pick-up','In conjunction with client request(s) the organization ensures that services provided and equipment and devices delivered to clients are communicated and scheduled with the client. Complaints regarding delivery/pick-up are noted, documented and reviewed.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(57,586,'del_5','DEL 5','Vehicle Maintenance, Labeling and Use','The organization ensures that all company owned and leased vehicles are safe, clean, organized and in good working order. The organization maintains records for all maintenance and repair performed on all vehicles. The organization ensures that staff are appropriately oriented, trained and evaluated regarding the operation of company vehicles. The organization provides exterior labeling of vehicles and proper signage and labeling when hazardous materials are being transported. In the event that the organization must use rental vehicles, appropriate signage and labeling is used.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(58,586,'ent_1','ENT 1','Required Information','Enteral nutrition products are only provided pursuant to a prescriber\'s order. The organization clearly defines the client information that is required for dispensing enteral products. The required information includes, but is not limited to:<ul><li>Client name</li><li>Date of birth</li><li>All relevant diagnoses pertaining to enteral product prescribed</li><li>Relevant medical history</li><li>Allergies</li><li>Nutritional status (for enteral or parenteral products)</li><li>Lot numbers of drug or product dispensed</li><li>Suitability of the home environment to the therapy being provided, safety concerns, presence of water, electricity, accessible telephone service, etc.</li><li>Any other pertinent or relevant information regarding the individual client that may affect or impact the client?s care</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(59,586,'ent_2','ENT 2','Provision of Enteral Products','The organization has an available and appropriately trained staff member who is knowledgeable and experienced in the clinical use of enteral nutrition therapy. All clients receiving enteral products are monitored for their response to treatment. The organization reviews the service plan periodically and along with the treating physician (as necessary), provides changes to the enteral nutrition therapy regimen when appropriate based on the client\'s response to the therapy. The organization will also:<ul><li>Document any changes to the prescribed enteral nutrition therapy per the prescribing physician. This includes, modifying the formula, dilution, administration method, flushing protocol, etc.</li><li>Document all client/physician contact and conversations in the client\'s medical record</li><li>Make monthly telephone calls to the client regarding their response to therapy</li><li>Make follow-up visits to the client when indicated</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(60,586,'rt_1','RT 1','Retail Services','Retail services are provided in clearly defined areas that allow for client or customer services. The organization ensures the staff and customers\' safety and security. The organization ensures:<ul><li>All public and private areas are clearly designated</li><li>All licenses, certificates and permits are displayed in an area visible to customers</li><li>Aisles and customer areas are clear of debris or inventory</li><li>Exit signs and escape routes are conspicuously posted</li><li>All trash dumpster areas are located apart from customer areas</li><li>Restrooms provided for customers are clean and organized with adequate lighting and supplies</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(61,586,'rt_2','RT 2','Producing a Receipt','The organization provides an immediate receipt to retail customers purchasing or renting equipment, devices, or supplies. This receipt contains all pertinent and relevant information necessary for the client to submit for third party reimbursement, including item numbers, codes and any additional specifications.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(62,586,'rt_3','RT 3','Processing Third Party Payer Claims','A list of all current third party payers with whom the organization participates is available upon request to retail customers.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(63,586,'rt_4','RT 4','Product Placement in Showroom','The organization ensures that all products for purchase that are displayed in retail areas are clearly marked with price and expiration date if applicable. The organization ensures that products that must be ordered are easily identified and the time frame that the client should expect to wait prior to receiving the ordered item is clearly explained.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(64,586,'rt_5','RT 5','Handling Product Returns in Retail Area','The organization handles product, equipment, or device returns in the retail area. The organization provides the customer with documentation that the return was made. The organization ensures that any returned item is examined and disposed of (if applicable), repaired or returned to the manufacturer as appropriate, before it is returned to inventory.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(65,586,'rt_6','RT 6','Handling Equipment Repairs in the Retail Area','If the organization provides repairs or adjustments in the retail area to equipment or devices brought in by the customer, they are performed in a designated area. The organization outlines infection control issues that need to be taken into consideration while performing repairs or adjustments.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(66,586,'re_1','RE 1','Appropriate Supply','The organization maintains an adequate assortment of appropriate products, equipment and devices for rehabilitation when applicable and provide(s) appropriate equipment for trial and simulation for the client, when necessary.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(67,586,'re_2','RE 2','Selection, Delivery, Set-up and Maintenance','The organization has policies and procedures in place that ensure that the selection, delivery, set-up and maintenance of rehabilitation equipment/devices are provided to patients in the appropriate environment. The organization maintains a repair shop located in the facility or in close proximity or easily accessible from another location of the supplier as well as an area appropriate for assembly and modification of products.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(68,586,'re_3','RE 3','Equipment/Device Fits','The organization verifies that all rehabilitation equipment selected and provided to the client as ordered by the physician adequately fits, meets the original specifications and can be used appropriately following manufacturer guidelines. If applicable, the organization provides the client private, clean, and safe rooms appropriate for fittings and evaluations.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(69,586,'re_4','RE 4','Training','The organization has policies and procedures in place that clearly describe any requirements for initial and ongoing training for any staff members providing any specialty fitting of rehabilitation or specialized equipment or devices including trained technicians available to service each location appropriately depending on the size and scope of its business. Examples of this include:<ul><li>Certified rehab technology supplier (CRTS)</li><li>Assistive technology professional (ATP)</li><li>Factory trained by manufacturers of the products supplied by the company</li><li>Experienced in the field of rehab technology, e.g. on the job training, familiarity with Rehab clients, products and services</li><li>Completed at least ten hours of continuing education specific to rehab technology</li><li>Able to program and repair sophisticated electronics associated with power wheelchairs, alternative drive controls, and power seating systems</li></ul>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(70,586,'crs_1','CRS 1','Scope of Clinical Respiratory Services Provided','The organization has specific policies and procedures to describe the clinical services provided and the scope of services provided. The organization follows the American Association for Respiratory Care (AARC) guidelines.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(71,586,'crs_2','CRS 2','Physician Ordered Treatment Plan','All clinical respiratory services are provided through a physician ordered treatment plan in coordination with equipment services and all relevant members of the healthcare team and with client input.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(72,586,'crs_3','CRS 3','Qualified Staff and Supervisor','All services and care provided for clinical respiratory services are performed by qualified respiratory staff members. All respiratory care staff members are supervised and evaluated by qualified persons.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(73,586,'crs_4','CRS 4','Clinical Support Services are Available 24 Hours/Day','When the organization provides clinical respiratory services, the organization maintains an on-call program with qualified and experienced clinical healthcare professionals available for after-hours calls from clients that operate 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(74,586,'co_1','CO 1','Treatment Preparation','The organization performs pre-treatment assessments, diagnostics and/or examinations of the client and collects all the necessary documentation including comprehensive and pertinent medical history (including allergies to materials), skin condition, diagnosis, previous use of an orthoses, results of diagnostic evaluations, beneficiary expectations, and any pre-photographic information as appropriate for the item. The appropriate orthoses is chosen based on the patient\'s need and optimum therapeutic benefit. Consideration must be given to the appropriate strength, durability, and function. Manufacturer\'s guidelines are followed regarding fitting. Safety instructions are given to the client prior to the fitting of the item (as needed). The implementation plan for the item is consistent with the physician\'s orders and treatment plan which will include an in-person, diagnosis-specific, functional examination as related to the beneficiaries need of the orthoses and establishment of a \"wear-schedule\" and tolerance of the orthoses. The organization must also provide the following specific instructions to the client:<ul><li>Use, maintenance and cleaning of the product</li><li>Placement and removal of the product to include adjustments of closures</li><li>Self-inspection of skin and use of supplemental materials designed to protect the skin such as protective cloth</li><li>How to report concerns, such as changes in skin condition, increased pain or edema, or overall tolerance of the product</li><li>How to request follow-up visits</li></ul><p>The organization demonstrates a process for referring the client to another organization if the client needs treatment or items outside of their scope of practice.</p>','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(75,586,'co_2','CO 2','Outcomes','The organization will establish goals and expected outcomes with the client, including documentation as to the client and physician\'s feedback including the desired goals and treatment as a component of the organization\'s quality improvement program.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(76,586,'co_3','CO 3','Treatment Plan Disclosure','The organization will have documented evidence of communication with the client about their treatment plan and any potential optional plans including the possible risks and the benefits. This communication is shared with the client and the prescribing physician. Referrals are made to the physician throughout the treatment, as appropriate and as dictated by the specific item.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(77,586,'co_4','CO 4','Continued Monitoring','The organization defines a period of time appropriate to the item where monitoring of the device and all client health issues associated with the device are tracked. The organization notifies the prescribing physician of health conditions that change or impede successful use of the device or item. Continued monitoring of the client is consistent with the diagnosis, care rendered and recommendations given.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(78,586,'co_5','CO 5','Supplementary Products','The organization supplies the necessary products for the client to manage, clean, attach or use the device, as directed. The client is made aware of how to access the supplies for future use.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(79,586,'co_6','CO 6','Adequate Supply','The organization maintains an adequate inventory of appropriate supplies, devices and supplemental products. The organization provides information to the client as to how any product modifications occur (as indicated) if not with the organization.','2012-01-01',1,NULL),
	(80,586,'civ_1','CIV 1','Compliance with AARC Guidelines','The organization has specific policies and procedures describing their ventilator care program. These policies and procedures comply with the American Association of Respiratory Care (AARC) guidelines and will include at a minimum a description of the equipment provided, the organization\'s scope of service and the description of the frequency of follow-up. The follow-up schedule is determined by the ongoing, individualized care plan and based upon the patient\'s current medical condition.','2014-01-07',1,NULL),
	(81,586,'civ_2','CIV 2','Admission to Service','The organization has established admission criteria specific to the care provided to ventilator patients. The organization has a policy that describes the admission process which includes at a minimum:<ul><li>Screening to ensure that the patient can be appropriately treated within the organization\'s scope of service</li><li>Physical assessment of patient and review of their medical history</li><li>Therapeutic goals</li><li>Home safety assessment to ensure the environment is safe and appropriate to the type of equipment</li><li>Evaluation of caregivers and support services involved in the care of the patient</li></ul>','2014-01-07',1,NULL),
	(82,586,'civ_3','CIV 3','Physician\'s Orders Treatment Plan','The organization provides care under medical direction. The organization will obtain physician orders with specific settings and parameters related to the equipment which includes but is not limited to the following:<ul><li>Ventilator mode</li><li>Volume</li><li>Rate</li><li>FIO<sub>2</sub></li><li>Pressure support (<em>when applicable</em>)</li><li>PEEP (<em>when applicable</em>)</li></ul><p>In addition the organization will obtain physician orders with specific direction regarding the clinical care to be provided. These orders include but are not limited to the following (<em>when applicable</em>):<ul><li>Pulse oximetry testing with frequency and acceptable ranges</li><li>End tidal CO<sub>2</sub> testing with frequency and acceptable ranges</li><li>Weaning activities including specific orders regarding taking the patient off the ventilator or changing settings for weaning purposes.</li><li>Frequency of obtaining weaning parameters</li></ul>','2014-01-07',1,NULL),
	(83,586,'civ_4','CIV 4','Ventilator Back-up Protocol','The organization has established protocols to provide back-up equipment which includes the following:<ul><li>A second ventilator is provided for patients who cannot maintain spontaneous ventilation for four or more consecutive hours.</li><li>A second ventilator is provided for patients who live in an area where a replacement ventilator cannot be provided within two hours.</li><li>A second ventilator is provided when the patient requires mechanical ventilation during mobility.</li><li>The organization has established a mathematical ratio in policy to define the number of back-up units available.</li></ul>','2014-01-07',1,NULL);
